  <section id="scouting">
    <h2 class="font-pixel text-[10px] text-arcade-cyan mb-4 leading-loose">// Scouting</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-arcade-text mb-6">
      <p>
        As a youth, I started in Cubs and then crossed over to Boy Scouts, earning the rank of Life before my family
        moved and I lost my connection to a troop. (Life for life!) It wasn't until years later that I realized just
        how much scouting had stayed with me.
      </p>
      <p>
        My adult scouting career began when my son, Evan, joined Cub Scouts and I became a den leader. When the den
        became Webelos and learned the Scout Oath and Scout Law, I was able to recite both from memory without
        hesitation despite not having said them in 25 years. When it was crossover time, Evan chose to join Troop 66. A
        few months into his time with the troop, I joined as an Assistant Scoutmaster. In 2021, I was asked to step up
        as Scoutmaster, a role I still hold today. Evan earned Eagle in 2024, aged out in 2025, and is now one of our
        ASMs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Troop 66 is a scout-led troop — my job is to advise and ensure safety, not to run the show. That philosophy
        has clearly worked: we have 28 scouts and 38 adult leaders, many of whom, like me, stuck around long after
        their own kids aged out. That says everything about what this troop means to the people in it. We're an
        extremely active troop between troop meetings, camping, service, and other activities.
      </p>
      <p>
        In early 2024, Evan and some friends founded Venture Crew 1212. I've joined as an Associate Advisor. It's a
        great front row seat to the scouts learning what all the adults did to keep the troop running now that they
        have to do it themselves.
      </p>
      <p>
        No matter the role, I love watching all of my scouts grow, develop skills, and become future leaders.
      </p>
    </div>
